Step 1: In the provided sample, the “Operating Cash Flow to Net Income Ratio” is calculated by dividing the Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities by the Net Profit. In the sample, both numbers were negative so that a division resulted in a positive ratio:
  Ratio = (–7,259,994.10) ÷ (–1,645,141.43) ≈ 4.41

Step 2: For the new problem we have:
 • Net Profit = 1,290,835.16 
 • Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –6,316,405.44

Step 3: Compute the ratio:
  Ratio = (–6,316,405.44) ÷ (1,290,835.16) ≈ –4.89

Thus, the Net Cash Ratio (calculated as Operating Cash Flow ÷ Net Profit) is approximately –4.89.
